<TITLE> Civil Service Act final draft by May </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 19 (bdnews24.com)--The final draft of the new Civil Service Act, designed to regulate jobs and other affairs of public servants, will be completed by May, a minister told parliament on Tuesday. "The government has taken initiatives to formulate the law to govern appointment, training, promotion, posting, transfer, salary, retirement of government officials and employees," local government minister Syed Ashraful Islam, who answers questions on establishment ministry, said. The question was put by Chittagong-11 MP Shamsul Haq Chowdhury. To another question by Joynal Abedin of Feni-2, the minister said one secretary has been forced to retire, and 10 secretaries and 12 additional secretaries made officer on special duty since Jan 1 last year. Syed Ashraf said there are 49 secretaries--12 of them acting--in various ministries and offices while two other secretarial posts lie vacant, in reply to Noakhali-6 MP Mohammed Fazlul Azim. In addition, there are 28 additional secretaries, 129 joint secretaries, 301 deputy secretaries and 719 assistant/senior assistant secretaries, he said to a question by Naogaon-6 MP Mohammed Israfil Alam. Civil servants from assistant secretaries to secretaries are posted to various government commissions, foreign missions, offices and departments as well as their need, according to the minister. So, the number of those posts is neither specific nor designated , he said. bd
